WEBVTT

00:01.398 --> 00:13.454
when non-black students were integrated into an 
all-white school after the 1954 Supreme Court

00:01.398 --> 00:13.454
ruling that separate was not equal and we should 
integrate with all deliberate speed, right?

00:15.296 --> 00:15.557
That's right. Okay. Well, do you want to start by 
telling us something about your background,

00:16.518 --> 00:25.870
about your education and your term as mayor and a 
little bit about the background of the Little Rock

00:16.518 --> 00:25.870
crisis? Born and raised in Little Rock. Went to 
public schools there. Graduated Little Rock

00:31.051 --> 00:35.281
Central High School in 1934. Went to University of 
Illinois. Graduated in 38 and worked in Chicago.

00:45.982 --> 00:51.932
Served as a naval officer in World War II and came 
back to Little Rock in December 1945. Became

00:53.615 --> 00:58.643
active in politics.

00:59.084 --> 01:01.468
Were you active in politics before you were mayor? 
Oh, yes. What kind of things did you do? Active in

01:05.835 --> 01:21.861
the Democratic Party, supporting and raising 
money for people seeking office on all levels, and

01:05.835 --> 01:21.861
then decided in 1955 to run for mayor of Little 
Rock. had planned to, within two to four years, run

01:23.495 --> 01:29.321
for governor of the state. That was my plan. Could 
you tell us a little bit about the background

01:31.463 --> 01:39.491
between the court case and when Faubus called in 
the guard? Well, when the Supreme Court ruled in

01:40.813 --> 01:50.042
1954 that the

01:52.739 --> 02:07.640
doctrine had been in effect for oh well and 
accessible hundred years that equal but separate

01:52.739 --> 02:07.640
facilities for whites and blacks was the way to run 
the educational system. Their decision changed

02:08.602 --> 02:16.333
it and said that the facilities for blacks were not 
equal to and in effect said that since the states

02:16.769 --> 02:35.786
are not willing nationwide to provide the money 
for blacks, that they were being deprived of their

02:16.769 --> 02:35.786
constitutional right for equal facilities for 
education, and that there should be a gradual

02:16.769 --> 02:35.786
integration of students regardless of color. And 
it was a very controversial decision in all parts

02:37.427 --> 02:46.135
of the country, not just the South.

02:47.954 --> 03:04.971
But since it was rooting of the Supreme Court,

02:47.954 --> 03:04.971
the states then and the individual school 
districts across the country began to put

02:47.954 --> 03:04.971
together gradual integration plans. At that 
particular time, a friend of mine named Bert

03:06.493 --> 03:17.944
Blossom was the superintendent of schools in 
Pulaski County.

03:19.072 --> 03:47.138
Even though he did not agree with the Supreme Court 
ruling, he accepted it as a so-called law of the

03:19.072 --> 03:47.138
land and

03:19.072 --> 03:47.138
put together a gradual plan that by meetings 
throughout the community, radio and television,

03:19.072 --> 03:47.138
over a period of a couple of years, the public knew 
about it. And there appeared to be no

03:47.877 --> 04:06.213
reason to believe that the plan which was adopted 
by the school board unanimously would meet any

03:47.877 --> 04:06.213
objection in the community or the city. Is this the 
way you felt? Any violence. That's what the school

04:08.395 --> 04:10.117
board felt. The school board voted unanimously 
after carrying it to the community. and even the

04:16.447 --> 04:22.517
newspapers agreed that the plan would be 
acceptable.

04:25.723 --> 04:40.648
Governor Faubus, who was already a controversial 
figure and was completing his first term as

04:25.723 --> 04:40.648
governor, had already agreed, or his second term 
as governor, has already agreed to step down and

04:41.455 --> 04:45.659
not seek re-election. And

04:47.301 --> 05:07.260
he decided with half a dozen or so friends that they 
would oppose the school board's decision or plan.

05:08.894 --> 05:20.486
He did this in such a dramatic fashion that he went 
on television on Sunday night before schools were

05:08.894 --> 05:20.486
to be integrated the following day in September of 
1957. And he said that there was rioting, that

05:20.506 --> 05:32.619
people across the country, across Arkansas and 
the whole state, the whole country would be coming

05:20.506 --> 05:32.619
in. There would be rioting on the streets and that 
people would be killed and slaughtered and so

05:33.120 --> 05:38.125
forth and so on. You say that perpetrated fraud 
upon the people of Little Rock particularly and

05:38.105 --> 05:47.507
the country as a whole because claim to those of us 
in the state involved with what was happening,

05:47.757 --> 06:03.437
that he was using this to perpetuate himself in 
offices as long as he wanted to be governor of the

05:47.757 --> 06:03.437
state of Marksville, which happened. He called in 
2,000 National Guardmen, and they surrounded the

06:03.497 --> 06:10.086
school.

06:11.180 --> 06:17.430
Were these half a dozen friends, were they 
political figures also or just personal friends

06:11.180 --> 06:17.430
of his? No, we met on what he announced on Sunday 
evening. And we called a meeting that night. And

06:32.593 --> 06:36.259
the governor of the state, no, the ex-governor of 
the state, Sid McMahon, the Lieutenant Governor

06:37.218 --> 06:59.335
of the state, I can't remember his name, one of the 
Senators, Congressman Brooks Hayes,

06:37.218 --> 06:59.335
Virgil Blossom, and most of the school board were 
present. And we

07:02.885 --> 07:10.956
were there to make some kind of decision how to meet 
the crisis that was certain to arise because the

07:02.885 --> 07:10.956
school was already surrounded. Because he came on 
television and said the school was surrounded

07:10.976 --> 07:15.101
just when it was. They were surrounded. Didn't he 
warn that blood would run in the streets of Little

07:16.182 --> 07:22.250
Rock if the blacks tried to enter the school? Yes. 
How did the crowd react to the guards being around

07:23.523 --> 07:26.786
the school? I mean, the guards themselves 
wouldn't let the kids through. And I read that one

07:31.390 --> 07:45.824
girl, Elizabeth Eckford, I believe is her name, 
came up and thought that the guards would protect

07:31.390 --> 07:45.824
her because she didn't realize what had been said 
in the student

07:31.390 --> 07:45.824
superintendent meeting. And she had tried to go 
through to the school anyway and felt that even the

07:46.725 --> 07:52.450
guards were giving her hate stares. Do you think 
that the guards had? They were there to keep them

07:53.812 --> 07:56.115
out. The guard was there to keep them out of school. 
But do you think that the guards had their, I mean,

07:58.798 --> 08:04.826
in their own opinion, were the guards against the 
National Guard? It's hard to say. It's hard to

08:07.008 --> 08:10.913
determine if the 2,000 were for or against it, but 
they had no choice. They were members of the

08:10.933 --> 08:13.937
National Guard, and they were called out by the 
government of the state. They had to be there. But

08:16.641 --> 08:20.125
they were instructed not to let them in school, not 
to escort them in. The only way in the world, this

08:20.830 --> 08:30.609
was a decision that was made that night, that the 
only way in the world they were going to get in was

08:20.830 --> 08:30.609
that, and this was done with Washington, D.C.'s 
approval. We were dealing directly with, at that

08:30.629 --> 08:37.282
point, Richard Nixon, who was vice president. 
Attorney General. I can't remember his first

08:39.983 --> 08:40.984
name. His last name was Rogers. I can't remember 
his first name. But it was determined that they

08:44.789 --> 08:48.855
would provide U.S. Marshals

08:48.915 --> 08:55.684
to assist those nine students. Did you call the 
President and ask him for support? Well, it was a

09:00.190 --> 09:02.332
spontaneous situation. The decision was made 
that night that we had to take immediate action and

09:02.392 --> 09:06.618
do something. Otherwise, we would have an awful 
lot of trouble. How long after the nine children

09:09.599 --> 09:18.531
tried to enter the school against the National 
Guard did it take before the troops came down and

09:09.599 --> 09:18.531
they actually got to go inside? I think a week or so. 
I'm not real sure. I'm not real sure. It didn't go on

09:24.159 --> 09:29.066
very long because nothing could happen. One of the 
things we would say, we called out Well, there were

09:33.173 --> 09:39.743
about 350 policemen at that particular time, 
about 350 firemen. And part of the plan agreed on

09:39.763 --> 10:00.396
was that we would call, use approximately 75% of 
the police force and the firemen, the police force

09:39.763 --> 10:00.396
with no guns, only with their, what do you call 
those? Not what you call the clubs or so forth and so

10:01.405 --> 10:04.908
on. They weren't called that. And the firemen only 
with fire hoses. And... Is that to ward off the mob?

10:12.275 --> 10:16.698
Yes, to prevent any mob violence and so forth and so 
on. But definitely no shooting because that would

10:16.758 --> 10:29.169
defeat what we're trying to do and that is to 
preserve peace and order and no violence and

10:16.758 --> 10:29.169
people being killed or injured. And... The 
strange thing about the whole situation was that

10:30.633 --> 10:39.527
when I, as mayor, ordered this to be done, the chief 
of police and the chief of the fire department both

10:30.633 --> 10:39.527
resigned. They would not do it. Because they 
didn't believe in the desegregation. Didn't

10:44.035 --> 10:45.998
believe in it. And we had to bring in assistance.

10:53.549 --> 11:02.242
How do you feel that this integration or the 
desegregation of Central High School could have

10:53.549 --> 11:02.242
taken place without the guard? Do you think it 
would have gone over smoothly? No problem. You

11:04.866 --> 11:06.609
don't think there would have been any problem? 
Whatever.

11:10.154 --> 11:15.642
The responsibility of the individual school 
districts was spelled out. the governor of the

11:16.448 --> 11:22.057
state and the federal government had no business 
at all interfering. It was not their

11:23.119 --> 11:24.601
responsibility. It was the responsibility of the 
board members and they'd already arrived at a

11:24.621 --> 11:27.646
plan. It had taken two years to make certain that 
the public agreed with and was familiar with the

11:28.387 --> 11:41.629
plan and that it would come off according to the way 
it had been explained many, many, many times. And

11:41.609 --> 11:56.431
had this action not been taken by the governor, 
there's no doubt in question at that time and now

11:41.609 --> 11:56.431
that it would have gone, you know, maybe some 
minor, but nothing unusual. Did you hear any

11:56.852 --> 12:01.018
rumors or anything of any violence that would have 
happened? Like, I mean, I know Fava's blew it way

12:01.339 --> 12:08.029
out of proportion that you didn't hear of hardly 
any. So, um... Oh, he had brought in 15 or 20

12:09.250 --> 12:24.448
people with a reputation of being 
rabble-rousers, we call them, to excite and

12:09.250 --> 12:24.448
incite rioting. As a matter of fact, the FBI knew 
that. And that was our job, to make certain that...

12:33.584 --> 12:58.242
bob did get excited and of course when it came on 
television the next morning there were triple

12:33.584 --> 12:58.242
thousand people out there just you know just going 
crazy you know going crazy i know there's so many

12:33.584 --> 12:58.242
people out there against the desegregation but 
were there a lot of people in the community that

12:33.584 --> 12:58.242
were for it that believed in it or were they most 
most of the most of the black people were obviously

12:33.584 --> 12:58.242
uh And a small percentage of the white people. You 
couldn't tell what percent. A lot of them didn't

13:04.132 --> 13:08.136
want to say anything because... A lot of people 
didn't care. Didn't bother. Didn't make a

13:08.456 --> 13:10.718
difference. What role do you feel that the media 
played in the... Did you think it was good or bad? I

13:15.002 --> 13:17.645
know that it showed the whole world. Grossly 
over-exaggerated. Oh, really? Locally,

13:19.727 --> 13:21.609
statewide, worldwide. You think it helped any? 
Grossly. All it did was... bring the situation to

13:28.563 --> 13:45.672
the attention of people that should have never 
been concerned about it, people that lived in

13:28.563 --> 13:45.672
other parts of the country, people who got 
involved that should have given it a second

13:28.563 --> 13:45.672
thought. It was a local matter. Just grossly 
over-exaggerated.

13:51.301 --> 13:53.625
The morning after it happened, after they 
integrated the school? After that particular day

13:56.136 --> 14:09.191
in September, the morning after it happened, 
there must have been 150 newsmen from all over the

13:56.136 --> 14:09.191
world in the mayor's office with television 
cameras. That's when I first met John Chancellor.

14:12.394 --> 14:13.395
Oh, really? I met him that day, and he was just a 
young man getting started. But they had him all

14:18.641 --> 14:20.083
over the world. They just wanted a scoop. They 
wanted some juicy gossip. That was it. That was the

14:23.947 --> 14:29.718
biggest news item worldwide. You were saying 
earlier that people just weren't accustomed to

14:30.299 --> 14:37.633
having blacks have any kind of freedom about 
eating lunch at any counters. No, no. Up until that

14:38.736 --> 14:44.166
point,

14:38.736 --> 14:44.166
the black people... all over the country, 
particularly the South. They didn't eat in

14:47.356 --> 14:50.040
restaurants. They didn't go to picture shows and 
sit in balconies. Public transportation, they

14:53.667 --> 15:00.479
sat in the back, including railroads, airplanes.

15:02.742 --> 15:05.968
And they were discriminated against. Had any of 
this started changing yet by the time that this

15:06.235 --> 15:10.380
little rock? Really not. I know one of the things 
that when I went in office as mayor in January of 56,

15:10.861 --> 15:32.388
for 150 years, the fountain, public fountains, 
water fountains, they were separate for black and

15:10.861 --> 15:32.388
for white. Restrooms were black and white, you 
know. We changed them all. During your... Within

15:40.579 --> 15:41.460
the first week. Oh. Within the first week, we 
changed. This was something that was done because

15:44.983 --> 16:07.545
I felt they were citizens of the city and that they 
paid taxes like anybody else and that there was no

15:44.983 --> 16:07.545
reason why when they walked in the city hall for any 
reason that they should have to go to a separate

15:44.983 --> 16:07.545
restroom or go to a... break water out of a 
separate... And there was nothing said about it.

16:10.327 --> 16:19.375
ignore press it was a lot of people felt 
differently that they should be different that

16:10.327 --> 16:19.375
they were different people How did you come to be so 
open-minded? Was it from your parents' views or

16:23.070 --> 16:28.841
from school or just your own personal 
disposition? No, I had grown up in a family of

16:29.602 --> 16:37.356
modest men. My father was in the commercialized 
business all of his adult life. He hired and worked

16:41.596 --> 16:50.344
with 15 to 25 people, and they were both black and 
white. And I didn't have any particular feelings

16:50.364 --> 16:58.052
about either way. I didn't realize in growing up 
what it meant to be discriminated against at that

16:58.192 --> 17:08.582
particular time. That's a neat view to see because 
you hardly ever hear about anyone who was

17:09.389 --> 17:18.762
open-minded about race relations at all during 
that time. Well, I went to school at the University

17:19.323 --> 17:25.993
of Illinois at North. I went to elementary and high 
school in Arkansas. There were no blacks in

17:29.818 --> 17:31.641
school. I went up there in almost every class. Uh, 
we would have a few black students involved with

17:36.625 --> 17:42.313
me. You know, some a reason why it should. They were 
just as radiant or more so than most of the white

17:43.855 --> 17:48.781
kids in college. They really didn't bother me. And 
I'd worked in Chicago and Illinois for four years

17:50.864 --> 17:56.912
before I went in service. Same thing, I worked with 
blacks. They mostly were white. I was a naval

18:03.299 --> 18:04.720
officer in World War II. And the same thing, we had 
black officers on the Admiral Dempsey's staff,

18:04.740 --> 18:11.167
which I served on for 18 or 19 months. And it didn't 
bother me. It really didn't bother me. Did it seem

18:15.031 --> 18:17.314
to bother other people that were on the staff with 
you? No. They were accepted, you know. How was

18:20.939 --> 18:23.923
Horace Mann High School? Was it in the books? Just 
as good or better than Little Rock High School.

18:29.452 --> 18:30.433
Just as good or better. A lot of the arguments seem 
to be that they had such a good high school, why did

18:31.154 --> 18:39.226
they want to come to the white high school that had 
more people and was older, not well-equipped? Was

18:39.247 --> 18:40.989
it separate but equal? It was equal. In what ways? 
Equal facilities. Probably... 90% of the black

18:50.318 --> 18:58.188
students going to Horseman High School did not 
want to go because they realized that they were not

18:50.318 --> 18:58.188
wanted there. They realized that. The nine 
students that started it? Well, 90% of the

19:02.793 --> 19:07.179
students at Horseman High School and other high 
schools realized they were not wanted. And

19:07.379 --> 19:09.642
they're no different than anybody else. You don't 
associate people that you don't particularly

19:12.065 --> 19:16.531
feel comfortable with. And they were the same way, 
exactly. But the National Association, what do

19:19.765 --> 19:25.337
they call it now? The NAACP was in its infancy at 
that particular time. And there was a nationwide

19:32.372 --> 19:38.685
movement, one of which was Martin Luther King. 
There was a nationwide movement to do something

19:38.868 --> 19:50.705
about civil rights, and education was where they 
wanted to start, which I did not agree with. I don't

19:50.785 --> 19:57.855
agree with today that you shouldn't take children 
and use them to advance the cause of the people as a

19:57.835 --> 20:08.028
rule. They should have taken grown people if they 
wanted to bring about equal civil rights and not

20:08.068 --> 20:24.568
use children, young children, six, eight, 10, 12, 
up through high school age, And I still remember

20:24.548 --> 20:34.888
that night when the NAACP was organized to do this 
very thing. And this Daisy Bates that you referred

20:34.908 --> 20:42.523
to a while ago, she was the leader. of the local 
community from NAACP. Oh, yeah. She was the

20:46.608 --> 20:47.729
leader. Well, was she a journalist also for a 
newspaper or something? Oh, you don't know? OK. We

20:52.154 --> 20:56.158
don't know that. But they were intent on seeing 
that schools were integrated. The kids could make

21:05.909 --> 21:08.956
a difference. They were satisfied with where they 
were. How were those nine kids selected? Do you

21:12.124 --> 21:13.527
remember? I don't know that. You don't know? I'm 
sure they had to volunteer because they knew there

21:17.015 --> 21:21.105
was going to be some problems. Did you ever meet 
those nine children? Never did. So, but you know

21:26.345 --> 21:35.661
that they, I mean, just from general, I mean, the 
general feeling that no one would want to be placed

21:26.345 --> 21:35.661
in that situation, but did you ever hear... I don't 
think they wanted to. But did you ever hear any

21:36.683 --> 21:44.596
stories about how they felt, if they were scared or 
proud to be the ones to make the difference? I think

21:44.616 --> 21:50.867
at that time, papers, radio and television 
interviewed them and... that they were concerned

21:52.653 --> 21:58.061
and afraid that they would be hurt. Had to be 
because even after the federal government sent in

21:58.081 --> 22:08.936
troops and stayed there for the rest, they stayed 
there the entire term. They stayed there through

22:09.056 --> 22:10.979
June, May of 1958. The troops then? The federal 
troops stayed that long. They were guarded in the

22:17.549 --> 22:21.394
classrooms, and they were guarded when they left 
the school. How were they received by the white

22:21.779 --> 22:24.907
students and the faculty? Was that all a farce 
because of the guards, or were they just not well

22:24.947 --> 22:31.404
received? Students didn't receive, didn't 
welcome the law. Most of them didn't. A handful

22:36.899 --> 22:39.264
did. The faculty mixed. Couldn't do much about it. 
In the lunchroom and places like that, did they eat

22:43.855 --> 22:49.949
separately? At a separate time or just off in a 
group by themselves? Separately. They did that in

22:53.978 --> 22:56.123
order to prevent any trouble. That's a good idea. 
Would you say, then you would definitely say that

22:59.867 --> 23:06.053
these students were even more segregated within 
the white school than they were outside? When we

23:06.774 --> 23:13.861
were talking about Hortzman High School, what 
kind of, did they have a mixed faculty or was it all

23:06.774 --> 23:13.861
black? All black. All black administration and 
everything? Everything.

23:21.169 --> 23:21.689
Okay. What other individuals do you think played a 
big part in the, for or against the desegregation

23:26.545 --> 23:29.231
movement. We mentioned Daisy Bates and Virgil 
Bloom. Blossom. Blossom. You mean locally or?

23:37.350 --> 23:37.771
Well, either.

23:43.243 --> 23:44.626
You mentioned Martin Luther King. I think the... I 
think that the, on the federal government level,

23:46.458 --> 24:12.381
between Richard Nixon and William Rogers, his 
name, he was attorney general, Bill Rogers at that

23:46.458 --> 24:12.381
particular time, they, they expressly felt that 
the Supreme Court ruling was the law of the land,

23:46.458 --> 24:12.381
which was questionable that it was the law of the 
land, and that they were It was their intent to see

24:12.884 --> 24:22.641
that, regardless of what took them, and do it, that 
it was going to be enforced, which was a great

24:12.884 --> 24:22.641
mistake, a great mistake. How do you think they 
should have gone about this whole situation? How

24:26.726 --> 24:28.969
do you think it would have been better or easier? 
Let the individual school boards across the

24:29.950 --> 24:40.000
United States take care of their own plan, and we 
wouldn't have had any problem at all. How long do

24:40.540 --> 24:49.149
you think it would have taken for the, especially 
the southern schools, to be integrated if they had

24:40.540 --> 24:49.149
gone at their own pace or own speed? Faster than it 
took. than it is what it has to last 25 years, 30

24:50.330 --> 24:54.921
years. Because they feel like it's something they 
have to do. Because any time you're forced to do

24:58.008 --> 25:02.879
anything, there's going to be resentment. And 
this was forced down the throats of the people

25:03.761 --> 25:08.372
across the country, north, south, east, and west. 
The North wasn't that different from the South as

25:09.770 --> 25:14.118
far as when it came to forced integration. But they 
try to make themselves seem better. People in the

25:17.805 --> 25:23.897
North were opposed to it more than the people in the 
South.

25:25.261 --> 25:31.710
The only reason the South got the attention 
because that's where, at that time, a great

25:25.261 --> 25:31.710
percentage of the black people lived. There 
weren't that many percentage-wise in the North

25:31.730 --> 25:47.573
and the East and the West, but they were bitterly 
opposed to it and it took them longer to achieve

25:31.730 --> 25:47.573
what degree of integration we have today. You said 
that the Guard stayed until May of 1958? No, no, no.

25:51.741 --> 25:54.285
The National Guard only stayed about a week or so 
until the Federal Troops moved in. Okay, but the

25:54.305 --> 25:55.548
Federal Troops stayed? The Federal Troops stayed 
when Eisenhower ordered Federal Troops in, and I

25:55.568 --> 26:06.388
can't remember how many there were, but they 
stayed until... School term was out in May. By the

26:09.488 --> 26:10.110
following year. And is that when the school was 
shut down that next term? There was no school at all

26:14.024 --> 26:16.975
for two years. There was no high school at all. 
None. Every high school was closed. In Little Rock

26:22.288 --> 26:24.751
or in Arkansas? In Little Rock. Because of the 
problem. How did the faculty and the students feel

26:29.498 --> 26:32.422
about the guards? Did they resent that or did they 
take that resentment that they had for the guards

26:32.462 --> 26:41.995
if there was any out on the black students because 
they were the whole reason that they were there?

26:43.173 --> 27:01.014
Well, I didn't actually talk to faculty members, 
but I'm certain that they did not agree with either

26:43.173 --> 27:01.014
the state or the federal government getting 
involved in the school administration properly,

26:43.173 --> 27:01.014
because that's strictly a local responsibility. 
